						<summary>

						<p>On a slab in the Dantēśvari temple.</p>						

						<p><hi rend="bold">Rāja Dikpāladēva Saṁvat 1760: 1703 A.D.</hi></p>						

						<p>This is a Maithilī rendering of No. 244 written by the <hi rend="italic">rājaguru,</hi> of Kākatīya family, who was a Maithila Paṇḍit.</p>						

						<p>This is dated in the Vikrama Saṁvat 1760. i.e., 1703 A.D. on the 3rd day of Baisākh, dark fortnight. This records the pilgrimage of Rāja Dikpāladēva to the Dantēśvari shrine when ‘so many thousands of buffaloes and goats were sacrificed that the waters of the Saṅkhinī river became red like <hi rend="italic">kusuma</hi> flowers and remained so for five days.’</p>						

						<p>The Kākatīyas are stated to be Sōmavaṁśīs, born of the Pāṇḍava Arjuna.</p>						

						<p>(Published in the <hi rend="italic">Ep. Ind.,</hi> Vol. IX., p. 164). </p>						

						</summary>
